Part 1: Codebooks

Data Overview

Provide an overview of your data set. What is it? How was it collected?

The data used in this study comes from a randomized controlled trial that aimed to compare the effectiveness of two types of therapy for insomnia - Acceptance and Commitment Therapy and Cognitive Behavioral Therapy. The data was collected online using REDCap. For this particular study, we selected a subset of variables from the baseline measurements, including age, sex, marital status, insomnia severity, anxiety, depression, and dysfunctional beliefs and attitudes about sleep. Our focus was on examining the relationship between dysfunctional beliefs and attitudes about sleep and insomnia severity.

Codebook

Using the codebook provided in class as a reference, document the variables (or a subset of the variables) for an ongoing (or completed) research project you are involved in. Please also make the âKeyâ and âOverviewâ sheets providing overviews of your study.

As a reminder, hereâs a description of the column names I traditionally use. Feel free to omit or add columns as you see fit:

  1. dataset: this column indexes the name of the dataset that you will be pulling the data from. This is important because we will use this info later on (see purrr tutorial) to load and clean specific data files. Even if you donât have multiple data sets, I believe consistency is more important and suggest using this.
  2. category: broad categories that different variables can be put into. Iâm a fan of naming them things like âoutcomeâ, âpredictorâ, âmoderatorâ, âdemographicâ, âproceduralâ, etc. but sometimes use more descriptive labels like âBig 5â to indicate the model from which the measures are derived.
  3. name: label is basically one level lower than category. So if the category is Big 5, the label would be, or example, âAâ for Agreeableness, âSWBâ for subjective well-being, etc. This column is most important and useful when you have multiple items in a scales, so Iâll typically leave this blank when something is a standalone variable (e.g.Â sex, single-item scales, etc.).
  4. item_name: This is the lowest level and most descriptive variable. It indicates which item in scale something is. So it may be âkindâ for Agreebleness or âsexâ for the demographic biological sex variable.
  5. old_name: this column is the name of the variable in the data you are pulling it from. This should be exact. The goal of this column is that it will allow us to select() variables from the original data file and rename them something that is more useful to us.
  6. item_text: this column is the original text that participants saw or a description of the item.
  7. scale: this column tells you what the scale of the variable is. Is it a numeric variable, a text variable, etc. This is helpful for knowing the plausible range.
  8. recode_text: sometimes, we want to recode variables for analyses (e.g.Â for categorical variables with many levels where sample sizes for some levels are too small to actually do anything with it). I use this column to note the kind of recoding Iâll do to a variable for transparency.
  9. recode: I write the R code Iâll parse by reading my codebook into R into this column.

Here are additional columns that will make our lives easier or are applicable to some but not all data sets:

  1. reverse: this column tells you whether items in a scale need to be reverse coded. I recommend coding this as 1 (leave alone) and -1 (reverse) for reasons that will become clear later.
  2. mini: this column represents the minimum value of scales that are numeric. Leave blank otherwise.
  3. maxi: this column represents the maximumv alue of scales that are numeric. Leave blank otherwise.
  4. year: for longitudinal data, we have several waves of data and the name of the same item across waves is often different, so itâs important to note to which wave an item belongs. You can do this by noting the wave (e.g.Â 1, 2, 3), but I prefer the actual year the data were collected (e.g.Â 2005, 2009, etc.)
  5. meta: Some datasets have a meta name, which essentially means a name that variable has across all waves to make it clear which variables are the same. They are not always useful as some data sets have meta names but no great way of extracting variables using them. But theyâre still typically useful to include in your codebook regardless.

Part 5: Recoding and Transformations

Using your codebook as a reference, recode, reverse score, or otherwise transform your variables as we did in class

Recode

Code
recode_fun <- function(rule, y){
  x <- y$value
  if(!is.na(rule)){y$value <- eval(parse(text = rule))}
  return(y)
}

data_recode <- data_2 %>%
  group_by(recode) %>% # group by the r code rule
  nest() %>% # create a nested data frame
  ungroup() %>% # ungroup() 
  # apply the recode function
  mutate(data = pmap(list(recode, data), recode_fun)) |> 
  unnest(data) |> 
    select(-recode)

Now look again at the descriptives using the describe() function or tidyverse functions.

Code
data_recode |> 
  dplyr::select(record_id, item_name, value) |> 
  tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = item_name,
                     values_from = value) |> 
  dplyr::select(-1) |> 
  psych::describe()

And the zero-order correlations:

Code
data_clean <- data_recode |> 
  dplyr::select(record_id, item_name, value) |> 
  tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = item_name,
                     values_from = value)

data_clean |> 
  dplyr::select(-1) |>

## Recode 

```{r recode}
recode_fun <- function(rule, y){
  x <- y$value
  if(!is.na(rule)){y$value <- eval(parse(text = rule))}
  return(y)
}

data_recode <- data_2 %>%
  group_by(recode) %>% # group by the r code rule
  nest() %>% # create a nested data frame
  ungroup() %>% # ungroup() 
  # apply the recode function
  mutate(data = pmap(list(recode, data), recode_fun)) |> 
  unnest(data) |> 
    select(-recode)
```

Now look again at the descriptives using the `describe()` function or `tidyverse` functions. 

```{r recode desc}
data_recode |> 
  dplyr::select(record_id, item_name, value) |> 
  tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = item_name,
                     values_from = value) |> 
  dplyr::select(-1) |> 
  psych::describe()
```

And the zero-order correlations:

```{r recode cors}
data_clean <- data_recode |>
```
